<datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="520">
<subfield code="a">
Collection of field recordings, photographs, and manuscripts created by ethnomusicologist Margarita Mazo. Mazo's research and fieldwork focuses on two sects of Spiritual Christians that split from the Russian Orthodox Church: Molokans and Old Believers. Mazo's research explores music and religious expression for these two religious sects and the ways diasporic communities maintain and adapt traditions. The collection includes documentation of Molokan and Old Believer communities in Stavropol, Tula, and Moscow, Russia and in Poland as well as diasporic Molokan and Old Believer communities in California, Oregon, and Pennsylvania in the United States.
</subfield>
</datafield>
<datafield ind1="8" ind2=" " tag="524">
<subfield code="a">
Margarita Mazo Old Believer and Molokan collection (AFC 2022/003), American Folklife Center, Library of Congress, Washington, D.C.
</subfield>
</datafield>
<datafield ind1="0" ind2=" " tag="506">
<subfield code="a">
Collection is open for research. To request materials, please contact the Folklife Reading Room at
</subfield>
<subfield code="u">https://hdl.loc.gov/loc.afc/folklife.contact</subfield>
</datafield>
<datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="540">
<subfield code="a">
The rights in this collection held by Margarita Mazo are goverened by copyright for the full duration under copyright law. Additionally, Molokan materials may not be duplicated without Mazo's permisssion. According to acquisitions forms on file with AFC, after Mazo's lifetime, permission for duplication of Molokan materials must be granted by the Molokan communities of origin. Rights belonging to third parties may be goverened by copyright and other restrictions.
</subfield>
</datafield>
<datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="541">
<subfield code="a">Margarita Mazo;</subfield>
